  "opinion": "As a man in his sixties who’s spent most of his life working as a cleaner and now runs his own small business in Lecce, I’ve learned that dealing with fake content on social media isn’t about tech skills—it’s about common sense and patience. My parents were both PhDs, so I grew up with a strong foundation in critical thinking, but that doesn’t mean I’m an expert on algorithms. When I see something that looks too good to be true—like a post claiming to offer free money or a health tip that seems too perfect—I remember my mother’s advice: 'Don’t trust what you don’t understand.' I’ve found that the best way to manage fake content is to pause, think, and check the source. For example, if a video claims to show a miracle cure, I don’t click on it; instead, I ask myself, 'Would this make sense to a person who’s not a doctor?' I also keep my eyes open for emotional manipulation—social media often tries to make you feel anxious or hopeful in ways that aren’t true. I’ve been married for many years, so I know how important it is to be careful with what I share online, especially with my family. My hobbies, like baking and cycling, remind me that life is simple and real—so why should social media be any different? I spend only a few times a week on social media, which helps me stay grounded. The key is to treat it like a conversation with friends: don’t jump to conclusions, and always verify before sharing. In the end, the most important thing is to stay true to yourself and your values, just as I do when I’m baking a cake or playing board games with my family.",
